  <section id="problem" data-nav="problem">
    <div class="wrapper">
      <div class="Grid Grid--gutters Grid--full Grid--gutter">
        <div class="Grid-cell">
          <div class="element">
            <div class="blankHXXS"></div>
            <%- include(`${templatePath}/shared/divider25`, {
            sectionName:'Problem',
            topSpacing:'spacingMedium',
            bottomSpacing:'spacingXLarge',
            topNbottomSpacing:''
            }) %>
          </div>
          <div class="spacingMedium"></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="Grid Grid--gutters Grid--full Grid--gutter">
        <div class="Grid-cell">
          <div class="element">
            <div class="blankHXXS"></div>



            <div class="spacingMedium"></div>

            <h1 class="fontWeight400">Problem</h1>
            <h4>The experience encouraged <span class="fontWeight400">item-first browsing</span> even though <span class="fontWeight400">price, availability, and fulfillment still depended on provider selection</span>, allowing users to build carts that felt complete before a bookable order actually existed.
            </h4>




          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="spacingMedium"></div>



        <div class="Grid-cell">
          <div class="element">
            <h3 class="fontWeight400 grey900">Marketplace model problem</h3>

            <h4>BabyQuip looked item-first, but fulfillment was still provider-dependent.</h4>
            <div class="marginLeft">
              <ul class="listCircle">
                <li>Users could browse gear first</li>
                <li>Users could add items first</li>
                <li>But price, availability, delivery, and fulfillment were not truly reliable until provider selection</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <img class="" src="screenshot_pricing_issue.png" alt="">
            <div class="specialCaseStudyTxt">
              <h5>The UI let users feel like they were building a real cart before the system had enough provider context to make the order real.
              </h5>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="spacingMedium"></div>
        <div class="Grid-cell">
          <div class="element">
            <h3 class="fontWeight400 grey900">Partner-entry problem</h3>

            <h4>Vrbo users were not typical BabyQuip browsers. They were using the mobile website inside the Vrbo app.</h4>
            <h4>They were mostly high-intent users because they had already booked lodging through Vrbo, but they might not know BabyQuip.</h4>
            <h4>Vrbo users carried over their hotel location, so they did not need the normal location gate. They entered mid-journey, but the product treated them like generic shoppers.</h4>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="spacingMedium"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="spacingMedium"></div>

      <div class="Grid Grid--gutters Grid--full Grid--gutter">
        <div class="Grid-cell">
          <div class="element">
            <div class="specialCaseStudyTxt">
              <h5> How do we help high-intent Vrbo users move from <span class="fontWeight400"> trip context → gear browsing → provider-backed </span> booking without false progress, repeated decisions, or loss of trust?
              </h5>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
